There’s something oddly satisfying about turning an ordinary slice of bread into a batch of crispy, savory chips. And when it comes to flavor-packed bread, rye steals the show. It’s earthy, tangy, and complex—exactly what you want when crafting a crunchy snack that can stand on its own or pair with your favorite dips. If you've never tried making chips out of rye bread, you're seriously missing out. But not all rye breads are created equal.
After countless Saturday afternoons of slicing, seasoning, and baking (and yes, a few burnt batches), I’ve narrowed down the best rye bread brands that transform beautifully into homemade chips.
Why Rye Bread Chips?
Before we dive into the brands, let’s talk about why rye bread makes such amazing chips. Compared to white or whole wheat, rye has:
A dense texture, which crisps up nicely without falling apart.
Bold flavor, especially if you go for seeded or dark rye.
Lower sugar content, which means fewer burnt edges.
Plus, there’s a nostalgic comfort in that deep rye taste—especially if, like me, you grew up with a German grandma who never went a day without a loaf on the table.
The Best Rye Bread Brands for Homemade Chips
1. Dave’s Killer Bread – Rye’s the One
If you like your chips to have a little personality, Rye’s the One delivers. It’s organic, non-GMO, and packed with seeds and whole grains that toast up beautifully. The slices are slightly thicker than average, which makes them ideal for sturdy chips.
Why it works:
Holds up well to baking
Crunchy edges, chewy centers (if you underbake slightly)
Nutty, hearty flavor
Pro tip: Cut into quarters, toss in olive oil, garlic powder, and smoked paprika, then bake at 375°F for about 10–12 minutes.
2. Pepperidge Farm – Jewish Rye
This one’s a classic. It’s not as dense as some artisan ryes, which means it gets extra crispy, especially when sliced into thin strips. It's the brand I reach for when making chips for a party spread—it’s reliable and always crowd-pleasing.
Why it works:
Balanced flavor—not too sour, not too bland
Slices uniformly, toasts evenly
Easy to find in most grocery stores
Great with: French onion dip or smoked salmon spread.
3. Alvarado Street Bakery – Sprouted Rye Seed
Sprouted grains? Yes, please. This bread leans into nutrition without sacrificing flavor, and it makes for a hearty, textured chip. The sesame and sunflower seeds on the crust give it that extra toasty crunch.
Why it works:
Rich rye flavor with a hint of sweetness
Sprouted grains = bonus fiber and nutrients
Slightly chewy when baked—great if you want a chip with some “bite”
Personal fave: Crumble these chips over a warm spinach salad for extra crunch.
4. Rubschlager Cocktail Rye
Tiny bread, big impact. These miniature square slices are adorably snack-sized and toast up into perfect one-bite chips. They're also ultra-convenient—no slicing needed!
Why it works:
Thin and consistent slices = even crisping
Classic deli-style rye flavor
Perfect for topping with cheese, tapenade, or hummus
Hosting hack: Toast these and serve as DIY chip “canapés” at your next get-together.
5. Trader Joe’s Sprouted Rye Multigrain
If you’ve got a Trader Joe’s nearby, do yourself a favor and grab this loaf. It’s hearty, earthy, and full of grains. It’s the kind of bread that makes you feel like you’re eating something your great-grandparents would approve of.
Why it works:
Deep flavor, holds seasoning well
Sprouted for better texture
Affordable and widely available
Topping tip: Brush with olive oil, sprinkle with everything bagel seasoning, and bake until golden.
How to Make Rye Bread Chips at Home
No matter which brand you choose, the method is pretty simple:
Slice it right – Go thin for super crispy chips, thicker for dippable ones.
Oil & season – A light coating of olive oil plus your favorite spices (garlic powder, onion salt, smoked paprika, za’atar… you name it).
Bake – 375°F for 10–15 minutes, flipping halfway through. Watch closely in the last few minutes—they go from golden to burnt real fast!
Cool – Let them rest for a few minutes. They crisp up more as they cool.
Final Thoughts
Rye bread chips are one of those snacks that feel gourmet but are deceptively simple. With the right loaf, a little oil, and your oven, you’ve got a crunchy, flavorful treat that beats anything in a bag. Whether you're grazing solo or hosting friends, choosing the right rye bread makes all the difference.
And if you’re anything like me, you’ll start with “just a few for dipping” and end up eating the whole tray straight off the pan.
